  "text": "The Role of Sse1 in Hsp90 Client Protein Fate Determination Sse1 functions as a NEF for Hsp70 and also as a passive molecular chaperone. To determine which of these two activities is involved in promoting protein kinase degradation in vivo, we used two previously characterized SSE1 mutant alleles. Sse1 containing the substitution K69Q binds ATP (but cannot hydrolyze it) and is capable of associating with Hsp70 and accelerating nucleotide exchange. A second mutant, G233D, does not bind ATP and does not form exchange complexes with Hsp70 [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Dragovic et al., 2006; [CITATION_3] . As reported previously, cells lacking SSE1 do not support activation of GR by the synthetic hormone analog deoxycorticosterone (DOC; Figure  3A ; [CITATION_4] . Although sse1-K69Q behaved essentially the same as wild type, introduction of the sse1-G233D mutant failed to restore GR activation, suggesting that Sse1 participates in GR maturation by virtue of its activity as a NEF for Hsp70. Identical results were obtained when mating pathway signaling through the endogenous Ste11 protein kinase was assayed. Although WT cells or sse1⌬ cells expressing plasmid-borne WT SSE1 or sse1-K69Q were responsive to the ␣-factor inducer, sse1⌬ cells bearing an empty vector or the sse1-G233D allele were not ( Figure 3B ).",
